result.execSummary:
The defendant Jimmy Kayastha was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Jimmy Kayastha is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Jimmy Kayastha was found guilty of Violate/Harassment Restraining Order, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 813.125(7).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:33 Defendant Jimmy Kayastha by phone with attorney Richard E. Bender in court.  Michael Daniel Zell appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Jason Parks Marshfield Police Dept appears by phone.

Detective Jason Parks is sworn as a witness.  Testifies to his employment with Marshfield Police Dept.  He is familiar with Jimmy Kayastha's cases.  Testifies to contact with the Police Dept in California that Jimmy was living in.  Testifies to the reason the California Police agency was investigating Jimmy.  

Atty Bender cross examines the witness.  Testifies to when he had conversation with California Police Agency.  Spoke with Jeff Cooley at Menlow Park Police Agency.  Testifies to what he forwarded to Det Cooley.  

Court questions Detective Parks.  Never received any information from Det Cooley.

Det Parks is released from phone call.  Court believes that Atty Bender is receiving everything based on testimony received.

Jimmy Kayastha is released from phone call.  Atty Bender indicates that Jimmy would like his items returned to him.  Atty Zell argues that it is not in Wood County's control to be returned to Jimmy.  Court believes the matter needs to be set for trial.  Atty Zell asks that the matters be set for 2 day trials on each case.  Parties to get the date from Branch 2 Judicial Assistant.
